d chisel marks are clearly visible, and along with wood shavings found inside the ship, point to new construction.The ship resembles the Kyrenia ship in some respects and the Bon-Porte and Gela ships in others; it was probably built in NW Turkey.','Remains of food','Rigging (including  3 wooden bobbin toggles), shipwright\'s tools and a one-armed wooden anchor with ropes still attached. The two instruments found on the shipwreck are the earliest preserved classical Greek measuring tools. The two units represented on the rule are identified as a Pheidonian and a Solonian foot, whose ratio may be correlated precisely to a statement by Aristotle about the metrological reform of Solon. The square used a shorter unit, identical to a measure known from Hellenistic and Roman times as the Italic foot, whose length was five-sixths of a Pheidonian foot. The notched subdivisions on the square suggest its originating standard was perhaps an archaic Greek foot, or 3 ft. multiple—a yard—first mentioned by Hesiod. The three standards represented on the shipwrecked tools indicate that Greek architects of the fifth century B.C.E. used multiple linear measures, traceable to diverse sources.','25',''),('Shipwreck528','La Macchi Tonda','La Macchi Tonda',41.9833333333,11.95,50,100,'',8020,'',613,'','','','','','','Roman Imperial','','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),('Shipwreck1828','La Maddalena','La Maddalena',41.25,9.4166666667,200,300,'C3rd AD',189,'422',614,'Tyrrhenian Sea','Italy','Most northerly point of Sardinia','','','Not reported','Roman Imperial','Bollettino di Archeologia 13-15 (1992), 213-4.','','','1','','','1','Fragments of slabs of marble in different sizes.','Some African tableware.','','','','',''),('Shipwreck1204','La Madonnina','La Madonnina',40.2833333333,17.5333333333,-325,-300,'C4th BC',8022,'',615,'','Italy','Puglia','','','','Hellenistic','http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 196, area 10','','1','0','','